        "content": "<p>Hello everyone,</p>\n<p>I would like to raise a concern regarding the current definition ofÂ <code>ConvexOn</code>Â in mathlib4. Specifically, I think the existing definition is somewhat restrictive and does not accommodate a broader class of functions, particularly those with values in the extended real numbers (<code>EReal</code>).</p>\n<h3><strong>Current</strong>Â ConvexOnÂ <strong>Definition</strong></h3>\n<p>TheÂ ConvexOnÂ definition in mathlib4 is as follows:<br>\n<a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/666dd63743750d3bf814c328bd6a1c86ffb52c8e/Mathlib/Analysis/Convex/Function.lean#L49-L52\">https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/666dd63743750d3bf814c328bd6a1c86ffb52c8e/Mathlib/Analysis/Convex/Function.lean#L49-L52</a></p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"sd\">/-- Convexity of functions -/</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ConvexOn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Prop</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">Convex</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆ§</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆ€</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">â¦ƒ</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"o\">â¦„,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆˆ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â†’</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆ€</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">â¦ƒ</span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">â¦„,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆˆ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">s</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â†’</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆ€</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">â¦ƒ</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ğ•œ</span><span class=\"o\">â¦„,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â‰¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â†’</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â‰¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â†’</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â†’</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â€¢</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â€¢</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â‰¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">a</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â€¢</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">b</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â€¢</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">y</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>This definition requires that for any two points within the <code>setÂ s</code>Â and any convex combination of these points, the function value at the combination is less than or equal to the convex combination of the function values at these points.</p>\n<h3><strong>Issue with</strong>Â EReal<strong>-Valued Functions</strong></h3>\n<p>Consider the following example of a function defined on the real line:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kd\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">â„</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">EReal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">Â Â </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â‰¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âˆ§</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">x</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">â‰¤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">then</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âŠ¥</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">else</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">âŠ¤</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Intuitively, according to <em>Convex Analysis</em> by Ralph Tyrell Rockafellar , this function should be convex because its epigraph (the set of points lying on or above its graph) is a convex set. However, according to the currentÂ <code>ConvexOn</code>Â definition in mathlib4, this function isÂ <strong>not</strong>Â recognized as convex. The reason is that when dealing withÂ ERealÂ values, expressions like<code>âŠ¤ + âŠ¥</code>become<code> âŠ¥</code>, causing the convexity condition to fail.</p>\n<p>I wonder if  there's a good way to solve this problem.</p>",
